HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 08-Feb-97 07:10:35 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 02-Jan-96 14:22:23 GMT
Content-length: 6186
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>
Latest Republican Outrage -- 12/22/95
 -- ACU</title>
<body>
<center>
<h3>Latest Republican Outrage -- 11/22/95</h3> 
<a href="#mail">Contact these Congressmembers</a>
<br>
<hr width="50%">
<br>
</center>

Should people be paid for work they didn't do?  Obviously, the answer is no.  But Republican
congressional leaders this week announced that, in keeping with the practice developed by
previous Democratic-controlled Congresses, furloughed federal employees will be paid for time
missed due to the government shutdown -- despite the fact that many are using their unscheduled
time off to fit in a little last-minute Christmas shopping.
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Robert Dole and House Speaker Newt Gingrich made the promise in a
letter they sent to Senator John Warner of Virginia, Congressmen Frank Wolf and Tom Davis of
Virginia, and Congresswoman Connie Morella of Maryland.  These four Republican Members of
Congress represent states and districts that are home to tens of thousands of furloughed federal
employees, and had been under the gun to ensure that their furloughed constituents would
continue to receive pay -- despite the fact that they are barred by law from working during a
government shutdown.
<P>
Knuckling under to the parochial political interests of these four Republican Members is an
outrage, and you should tell them so.  Call, write, or send an e-mail letter to Sen. Dole and Rep.
Gingrich telling them you disagree with the policy of using your hard-earned tax dollars to pay
people for not working.
<P>
The whole idea is noxious.  Americans believe deeply in fairness, and many have suggested that
because it's through no fault of their own that they've been furloughed, federal employees
shouldn't bear the cost of the shutdown.  But this facile reasoning overlooks the fact that
Montgomery County, in Maryland, and Fairfax County, in Virginia, are the two richest counties
in the country, due to the fact that they are home to huge numbers of federal employees, whose
median income is far above those of ordinary Americans.
<P>
Let's face it:  federal employees have some of the cushiest jobs around.  They have virtually total
job security, higher pay scales, less stressful work loads, and better health care and other fringe
benefits than the overwhelming majority of American workers.  There's virtually no risk
involved in taking a job with the federal bureaucracy -- a lack of risk totally alien and not
understandable to most Americans, whose jobs in the private sector are at risk every day.
<P>
Taking a risk of losing a day's or a week's work and pay every few years in the event of a
shutdown seems a small price to pay to hold one of these cushy federal jobs.
<P>
More importantly, what's fair about taking tax dollars from workers all over America to pay
people who aren't working?  Nothing.  In fact, it's UNFAIR to forcibly collect taxes from
Americans who actually work in the private sector to redistribute their income to people who are
out doing their Christmas shopping.
<P>
During the first government shutdown, the potential savings in wages of furloughed federal
employees amounted to $120 million per day.  Over the six-day shutdown, GOP leaders had the
opportunity to save the taxpayers almost three-quarters of a billion dollars, simply by not paying
furloughed employees for work they didn't do.  During this second shutdown -- in which only
260,000 employees are idled (as opposed to the 800,000 last time) -- the potential savings
amount to $40 million per day ... a smaller amount, to be sure, but still not chump change.
<P>
Clearly, Mr. Dole, Mr. Gingrich, and other weak-kneed Republicans are worried about the public
relations drive that would be mounted against them should they refuse to fund back pay.  The
establishment media would have a field day with reports of how "heartless Republican leaders"
abandoned hard-working, honest federal employees a week before Christmas.
<P>
But GOP leaders could turn the debate on a simple question:  with whom do you stand, the
relatively small number of federal employees, or the tens of millions working Americans whose
wallets are being picked to pay for early Christmas vacations for federal workers?  In other
words, do you care more about those inside the Beltway, or those outside?
<P>
We already know that the Democratic Party is the party of government.  We EXPECT
Democrats to take taxpayer dollars to redistribute to federal bureaucrats taking a bonus
Christmas vacation.
<P>
But Republicans claim to be the party of taxpayers.  They should know better.  By siding with
vacationing federal workers against the tens of millions of Americans who are working hard this
week to be able to buy their children Christmas presents, they insult all of us.
<P>
We believe this taxpayer rip-off is an outrage, and urge you to tell them what you think.
<P>
<center>
