<html>
<head>
<title>
Latest Republican Outrage -- 10/24/95
 -- ACU</title>
<body>
<center>
<h3>Latest Republican Outrage -- 10/24/95</h3> 
<a href="#mail">Send the Senators E-Mail</a>
<br><br>
</center>
Bill Clinton wants to send up to 25,000 U.S. troops to monitor and enforce a so-called "peacekeeping agreement" in the troubled nation of Bosnia -- and unless you act today, he may be able to do it without congressional approval!


When the House considered and passed its version of the Fiscal Year 1996 Defense Appropriations Bill, H.R. 2126, the bill included language authored by Wisconsin Rep. Mark Neumann, one of the GOP's conservative rising stars, which included a prohibition a

gainst such a decision.  That language stated:<p>

<i>     Sec. 8102.  None of the funds available to the Department of Defense shall be obligated or expended for the purpose of deploying United States Armed Forces to participate in the implementation of a negotiated peace settlement in Bosnia-Herzegovina, unless such deployment is previously authorized by law.</i><p>



But when the Senate and House negotiators met to discuss their differences, the Senate conferees -- led by Alaska Republican Ted Stevens -- objected to the prohibition, and instead substituted a much weaker "Sense of the Congress" resolution, in effect 
merely recommending to the President that he obtain congressional approval before sending troops.

This is an outrage.  Millions of Americans are still wondering exactly what is the U.S. vital national security interest that justifies putting tens of thousands of soldiers, sailors, airmen, and Marines in harm's way?  Would they be under the command of 

U.S. officers, or, as many fear, foreign nationals?  How long would they be there?  Under what Rules of Engagement?  And how are we to pay for this operation -- an exercise which, according to press reports (the only information we have, because the 

Administration has so far failed to release the information), could cost as much as $2 billion?

These questions and others remain unanswered.  The President has yet to make his case to the American people, answering these questions and explaining just what exactly it is he hopes to achieve by risking our troops' lives, and why he believes we should 

do it.<p>

That's nothing new -- we expect that sort of behavior from Bill Clinton.  What disturbs us is that Senate Republicans, led by Sen. Stevens, have let the President off the hook.

When the House took up the Defense Appropriations Conference Report on September 29, it defeated the measure overwhelmingly, in large measure because many Republicans voted against it on the grounds that the prohibition had been removed and replaced with 

a weak-kneed Sense of the Congress resolution.  We commend those Republicans for their courage.

And we urge to take advantage of the opportunity afforded us by their courage.  The Defense Appropriations Conference Committee will meet again soon, to consider rewriting certain sections of the bill in an effort to get it passed.  Write or call the Sena

tors below and urge them to hold to the original House-passed language on Bosnia, to ensure that no U.S. forces are sent without an explicit vote of approval from both Houses of Congress.

<b>
<p>Defense Appropriations Conferees in need of attention:<p></b>

<a name="mail"></a>
Sen. Ted Stevens<br>
<a href="mailto:specter@bizserve.com">Sen. Arlen Specter</a><br>
Sen. Mark Hatfield<br>
<a href="mailto:senator_domenici@domenici.senate.gov">
Sen. Pete Domenici<br></a>
<br>



Write or call them today, or U.S. troops could be in Bosnia before we know it -- without Congress ever having a chance to debate and vote on the issue!
<br>
<br>

[ <a href="/conservative/welcome.html">ACU Home</a> | <a href="i-libout.html"> Latest Outrage</a> ]
