HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 08-Feb-97 07:12:54 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 16-Aug-96 14:17:45 GMT
Content-length: 5842
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Devine: GOP's Platform Feuding -- 8/10/96 -- ACU </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>August 10, 1996</I><BR>
<P><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>Momentous Welfare Decision</STRONG></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG>Agonies of the Majority</STRONG></FONT>
<P><STRONG>Donald Devine</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
With their platform committee meeting today, one question is on every lip: Why are the Republicans fighting over every issue?  Political analyst, Samuel Lubell explained it all many years ago: "The key to the political warfare of any particular period will be found in the conflict among the clashing elements of the majority party."  Democrats used to have raucous conventions when they were the majority.  Now the GOP is where contesting factions compete.  "That these elements can continue in alliance seems to defy every law of logic. But like the sun, this apparently unstable political mass has its own gravitational equilibrium."
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
While there are pro-life Democrats, several such members of congress had to meet secretly with their party chairman rather than raise a public issue.  Rather than get in a public argument against the dominant Democratic pro-choice faction, vague "tolerance" language was quietly added by their platform committee.  On the Republican side, the minority pro-abortion rights faction is in the headlines every day or so disputing the existing pro-life language even though the presidential nominee, Bob Dole, said he wanted to leave it unchanged.  To assuage the pro-choicers, he originally agreed to add language to indicate Republicans differ on issues like abortion and term limits.  Govs. Pete Wilson of California and William Weld of Massachusetts insisted publicly the limitation only refer to the abortion issue and there was movement toward their position.  Then pro-life leaders like Pat Buchanan, Phyllis Schlafly and James Dobson criticized that concession and the position moved right again.  The bickering will last until the document is finalized.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The abortion debate is the most public but it is by no means unique.  Mr. Buchanan figures prominently in two other contentious issues.  Immigration will divide the GOP, as the recent Senate consideration demonstrated.  While the mood for limits has been growing, a restrictive bill was delayed by a band of open-immigration Republicans fighting the trend.  Mr. Buchanan knows he is riding a popular issue here and can be expected to make points on it again.  If he was successful obtaining his language to secure the border in 1992, he will demand more in 1996.  Trade and protectionism will loom as even more contentious.  Here Messrs. Dole and Buchanan differ directly upon GATT and NAFTA trade agreements.  Mr. Dole has the votes, but so did George Bush when Mr. Buchanan was able even to have his slogan, "America First," placed in the platform.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Welfare is supposed to be pretty much a consensus issue for Republicans.  Do not believe it.  The major divide is not even with the moderates, as it is in the Senate.  It primarily sunders the limited-government/economic conservatives from the Religious-Right/social conservatives.  The former stress sending programs to the states, communities and private charity without national rules, preferably devolving the whole program, but failing that, by "clean" block grants leaving decisions to the states.  Social conservatives support block grants but insist upon national regulations discouraging anti-social behavior like illegitimacy.  Presumably these differences, too, will surface at the convention as they have in Congress.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Even the central issue of taxes raises fundamental issues among Republicans.  There is support for a flat tax of the Dick Armey-Steve Forbes variety, that is flat across the board with few or no exceptions, or at least one with two rates, or with more exemptions of the "flatter and fairer" variety.  Almost directly opposed is a proposal by Sen. Dan Coats to increase charitable deductions dramatically to allow individuals to direct taxes to private welfare rather than to government welfare programs.  even more radically opposed is Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer's proposal to repeal the 16th Amendment, to eliminate the income tax and shift to a consumption-sales tax.  If there is no income tax, it hardly can be flat or even flatter.  Supply-siders go in a very different direction, demanding a large, across-the-board marginal income tax decrease to spur economic growth.  The Committee for a Conservative Platform, seeking to bridge the gap, has developed "principles" that appear to cover each of these positions, but it remains to be seen whether it satisfies all factions.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
There are also property rights advocates opposing environmental regulators, many gun control differences, labor and employment divides, and many other issues over which Republicans disagree.  Democrats pretty much have a standard party line.  It was simpler for the GOP when it was in the minority.  The highest value was either imposing the nominee's position or ideological uniformity.  Both are more difficult in a more disorganized majority party.  That is why humorist, Will Rogers, could quip: "I belong to no organized party.  I am a Democrat."  But, then, Democrats won.  Today, the disorganization, debate and differences are in the GOP.  The good news is, if Republicans are as artful as the old Democrats, the victories should be with them too.
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>[ <a href="/conservative/">ACU Home</a> ]
</BODY>
