<html>
<head>
<title>Devine: Momentous Welfare Decision -- 6/26/96 - ACU
</title>
</head>
<body>


<blockquote><blockquote>


<I>June 26,1996</i><br>



<center>
<h2>
Momentous Welfare Decision
</h2>

<b>Donald Devine</b>
</center>

<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
House of Representatives GOP leaders will make a decision this Wednesday that will
have a momentous effect upon the Presidential race. It will also determine whether  the Party's
major support groups can be motivated even for the Congressional races, and whether the leaders
will give priority to the more-vulnerable House Freshmen or the more secure, senior moderates.
Rarely does a tactical legislative decision so broadly affect a political party's future.

<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The immediate issue seems mundane. Four options have been presented to the entire
Republican caucus regarding welfare reform: support either (1) the governors' consensus welfare
reform (with details still not made public), including Medicaid devolution to the states and the
$500 per child tax credit provision promised in the Contract With America; (2) welfare and
Medicaid reform, but decide that the tax credit is not germane to welfare reform; (3) welfare
reform only; or (4) leave welfare reform for the next session and only work on appropriation bills
for the remainder of this Congress. Really boring stuff; but the implications are enormous--because each option has a different, hidden political premise. 

<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Supporting a bill combining welfare, Medicaid and tax reform (or even just the first two)
assumes that President Bill Clinton will find the legislation objectionable and force his veto. This
assures that welfare reform will be an issue of great importance in the 1996 Presidential election.
"Bill Clinton promised to 'end welfare as we know it' but vetoed reform three times. Only a
Republican President will deliver true welfare reform." Including the tax credit additionally
targets a constituency--especially, among social conservatives--who were promised middle class
tax reduction but were frustrated by the President once again from obtaining any relief. The
Freshmen ran on a Contract that promised all three changes and would have Bill Clinton placed
again on record making reform impossible. Either of these strategies sets up an election on issues
favorable to the Congressional and Presidential GOP.

<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The problem is that some moderates genuinely are opposed to Medicaid and tax credit
reform. Others simply fear another losing confrontation with the President. Groups like the
American Conservative Union consider that welfare reform without Medicaid reform is a sham,
since the later is the far-larger part of welfare, broadly considered. The Christian Coalition
believes that the $500 child credit was the only part of the Contract With America aimed at them
and that reform without it ignores its constituency. Republican supporters of the "welfare-only"
solution want to show the voters they have "delivered" on welfare reform. With all of the
disagreement,  the consequences for the Presidential race are either overlooked or cynically
ignored. The assumption is that Bill Clinton will sign a welfare-only bill. This means President
Clinton has fulfilled his promise on welfare. That leaves Bob Dole without one of his most
potent campaign issues. It is a strategy to elect a Republican Congress and a Democratic
President.

<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The House leadership is genuinely in a bind. The votes are probably not there for real
reform so the tendency is to show we in Congress "did something" and let the Presidential race
take care of itself. This is shortsighted. If  Mr. Dole does not run well, he will drag down House
and Senate candidates too, leading to a loss of the House. Assuming there is no majority in the
Senate for real reform, the only rational solution even from the perspective of Congressional
candidates is option four. Mr. Clinton has vetoed welfare reform twice. That puts him on record.
And it was the Republican Congress that twice passed bills he could have signed. That proves the
GOP did vote to end welfare as we know it; but Bill Clinton insisted upon more ruinous and
wasteful welfare.

<p>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Deep down, Republicans know there cannot be real welfare reform without a Republican
President. Voters are not fools either. If Bill Clinton is reelected, it will be clear to voters nothing
changed with the welfare-only bill. How will House members explain that in 1998? Like it or
not, Congressional and Presidential campaigns are intertwined. The only valid strategy is to work
on the appropriations bills now  and prepare for real welfare reform in 1997, after electing a
Republican President who will sign it.

<p></br><p>

</blockquote></blockquote>


</center>[ <a href="/conservative/i-col.html">ACU Columnists</a> | <a href="/conservative/welcome.html">ACU Home</a> ]<p>
</center><p>
<p><p>
</body>
</html>
