<html>
<head>
<title>Re: Abortion Statement in Platform - Donald Devine</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#00009c">


<center>
<b>To: Conservative and Republican Leaders</b>
<h2>Re: Abortion Statement in Platform</h2>
<b><i>by  Donald Devine</i></b><p><i>May 13, 1996</i><br><p>
</center>

<br>

<OL> 
<p>
<li><i>Working the Media Frenzy.</i><p>
 Every savvy Washington operator knows the one sure way to make
"news" is to touch the media raw nerve on the abortion issue. The elite polls show the media are
rabidly in favor of abortion "rights," with only 14% quietly pro-life. When liberal Sen. Pat
Moynihan labels partial birth abortions "too close to infanticide," it is not news. If you
threaten to liberalize the Republican platform on abortion, a GOP politician is guaranteed
massive, favorable publicity. The temptation is great for the weak.
<p>
<li><i>Complaining About the Platform Gets Rid of the Issue?</i> <p>
The cutest way for a governor, senator
or whoever to spin the story is to say you want to eliminate abortion as an issue, as you take
the story to the front page and TV leading item. As if eliminating it from the platform would
not create controversy. Needless to say, there is no better way to divide the GOP and
conservatives. Pro-choice GOPers are scraped sore again, being reminded they are in a minority,
while the pro-lifers are sure there will be a "sell out." What a way to run a political
party--irritating all sides!
<p>
<li><i>They Do It At Every Convention.</i><p>
 I have been deeply involved in every Convention since 1972
and the "shoot the wounded Republicans" have dominated the media in all six. Before the abortion
controversy, it was racial quotas and affirmative action. The issues change but the posture of
attacking the party over winning issues that cannot be altered does not. Opportunists will
always be with us, even when the party finally has President Clinton on the run--in this case,
over his partial-birth abortion ban veto.
<p>
<li><i>There Will Be An Anti-Abortion Platform, Period. </i><p>
Senator Bob Dole has said there will be a
pro-life platform (W. Post, 5/6/96) and that will settle it. A majority of delegates will
support it too. Even smart politicians with reservations about the pro-life plank say it would
be a political mistake to change the principles because the candidate would look equivocating.
<p>
<li><i>Changing the Wording Does Not Equal Abandoning Principle.</i><p>
Maintaining the principles of the
anti-abortion statement in the platform does not mean every last word and comma must remain the
same. I was involved in the politics of the earlier wordings and there was nothing sacrosanct in
their creation. If the wording can pass Congressman Henry Hyde's muster, it should suffice for
pro-lifers.
<p>
<li><i>The Point Should Be To Win the 1996 Election, Shouldn't It?</i> <p>
OK, there is disagreement on the
abortion issue. A party settles such differences by majority vote and candidate position on the
issue. That has been decided pro-life for 1996. The minority pro-choice faction must put the
issue behind them for now and await another day. Today, the job should be to win the election in
1996 and unite behind the majority position on the issues each can support.

<P>
<center>1007 Cameron Street, Alexandria, VA 22314<br>
PHONE: (703) 836-8602 FAX: (703) 836-8608<br>
E-Mail: <a href="mailto:info@conservative.org">info@conservative.org</a> WWW: <a href="http://www.conservative.org">http://www.conservative.org</a><p>

[ <a href="/conservative/">ACU Home Page</a> ]</center>
</body>
</html> 
