<title>Daily Commentary - January 23, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 23, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Yesterday marked the 24th anniversary of the Supreme Court's
<I>Roe v. Wade</I> decision.  And for the 24th time tens of 
thousands gathered in Washington to protest the deaths of 
millions of children from abortion.

<p>

Over the past 30 years, demonstrators have acquired a bad reputation.
The turbulent anti-war protests of the 60s, along with extremist movements
like radical environmentalism and the animal rights crowd, have caused many
of us to view protesters with suspicion.

<p>

But yesterday's peaceful March for Life was different.  The marchers
weren't demanding special benefits for themselves. Nor were they demanding
that society embrace some bizarre social agenda.  Instead Americans from all
walks of life gathered in the nation's capital for the most unselfish of 
reasons: to defend innocent human life.

<p>

I think these men and women are the conscience of America.  They
remind us that all men are endowed by their creator with &quot;certain
unalienable rights,&quot; which include, &quot;life, liberty and
the pursuit of happiness.&quot;  They also remind us that the
contradiction between the principles of the Declaration of Independence,
and the practice of legal abortion, must be resolved in favor
of life.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

