<title>Daily Commentary - January 27, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 27, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

It's time to get down to business. Here in Washington, Congress
is back in session, and the president has been sworn in along with 
his new cabinet.

<p>

But lately this city has been preoccupied with scandals.  The
past few weeks have focused largely on Newt Gingrich.  The next few 
weeks will likely focus on the range of ethical problems at the White 
House.

<p>

Authorities will continue their investigations in these matters -- and
they should. But now it's time for Congress and the president to focus 
on the people's business.  I for one want to see immediate action on 
protecting unborn children, tax relief for America's families and 
measures to protect marriage.  We also need a serious judicial reform 
effort. We need to rein in judges who have taken legislative power away
from the people. And it's past time to do something about wasteful 
government spending.  We should start by insisting that the president 
set a better example than he did when he blew $12 million of the 
people's money for his second inauguration.

<p>

There are no more excuses; it's time for our leaders to get back
to work.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

