<title>Daily Commentary - January 30, 1997</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
January 30, 1997</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

You know, it's difficult for a free people to imagine not being
able to speak out against corrupt politicians.  But in China,
a billion people are under the thumb of an oppressive government,
and they dare not say a word about it.

<p>

A report by the State Department shows there are no dissidents
left in China.  They've all been jailed or exiled.  In 1989, we
watched in amazement the courage of Chinese students who marched
in Tienanmen Square.  Today, they are all gone.

<p>

During their struggle, they looked to us for inspiration.  They
quoted our Declaration of Independence and built a paper-mache
model of our Statue of Liberty.

<p>

But U.S. policy makers answer with cold economic theories to
solve China's abuses of human rights.  We've allowed corporate
projections of huge profits to drive our policy.  And in doing
so, we've ignored everything from forced abortion to China's sale
of dangerous weapons to our sworn enemies.

<p>

My friends, I know America is better than that.   Our leaders
must have the courage to confront China's abuses.  The price of
not doing so is simply too high.

<p>

For Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with today's
Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call 1-800-225-4008.
That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

