<title>January 23, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 23, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>CLINTON ADMINISTRATION HAS DOUBLE<br>
STANDARD ON SCHOOL STANDARDS, NOTES FRC</h2></center>

<p>

<b>WASHINGTON, D.C. --</b> &quot;Bill Clinton exhibits selective
memory on the issue of academic standards, but on one thing we
agree, local control of our schools is an important tradition
and condition for school success,&quot; Family Research Council
Gary L. Bauer said Thursday, following Clinton's remarks on national
standards.

<p>

<b>&quot;We all agree that we need high standards for our children's
education. The critical  question is whose standards?</b> For
example, the state of Ohio set the standard that all high school
graduates be required to pass a ninth-grade proficiency test.
One of Clinton's federal agencies thought that was too high and
took the state to court.

<p>

<b>&quot;This raises the important question, will our children
be better educated with a Clinton standard?</b> Today in America,
we have the general standard that children learn to read by the
end of first grade. Bill Clinton proposed a $2.75 billion new
program to use paid 'volunteer' tutors to get kids reading by
the end of third grade. But isn't that what tax payers expect
teachers to do?

<p>

&quot;The president also called for more testing, but already,
regular testing shows that America's kids are falling behind other
nations. Perhaps Bill Clinton would join FRC in supporting standards
for teachers and in giving schools the authority to evaluate teacher
performance.

<p>

&quot;Recent controversy surrounds the dumbing down of standard
tests such as the SAT. There are no guarantees that the testing
Clinton advocates will not be altered to achieve certain results.
<B>All tests are not equal</B>. The answer to our current problems
is not to strengthen federal bureaucrats at the expense of parents
who love their children and local teachers who work with families
daily.

<p>

&quot;Frankly, I'd like to hear the president explain how he plans
to set national standards while strengthening local control. You
can't have it both ways. Currently, the federal government puts
in about seven cents of the education dollar spent at the local
level. And those seven cents are used as a powerful carrot and
stick on our schools. Where has that carrot led us?

<p>

&quot;<b>Recent history is clear. The more the federal government
has become involved in our schools, the poorer the students have
performed</b>. It's time to strengthen the parents, local educators
and state leaders who are on the front lines and are committed
to making a difference for our kids.&quot;

<p>

<center><h4>FOR MORE INFORMATION OR INTERVIEWS,<br>
CONTACT THE FRC MEDIA OFFICE AT (202) 393-2100.</h4></center>

<p>

