<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 31, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>




<LI>In a recent C-SPAN  interview, Hillary Clinton confessed a love of housekeeping (reminiscent of her 1992 fondness for baking cookies). "I mean, it's partly because there's a beginning, a middle and an end," she cooed, "so that we'll clean out closets together." Skeleton after skeleton.
<P>
<LI>Student-loan default rates have plunged to 10.7 per cent, their lowest rate ever, and less than half their 1990 level. As a result the government spent $249 million covering delinquent student loans last year, compared with $1.7 billion four years earlier. Credit Congress. In 1990 lawmakers authorized hardball tactics, including the withholding of income-tax refunds from defaulters, filing lawsuits against delinquent students, and making schools with high default rates ineligible for the federal loan program. Inevitably some deserving students will find it harder to pay tuition. But the crackdown, by shrinking a too-ample safety net, also makes it harder for colleges to raise tuition. Over the long haul, that is the only way to shrink this nut.

</blockquote>


