<html>

<title>REAL WORLD FRIENDS</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>REAL WORLD FRIENDS</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Larry H. Huff</i></center>

<p>

The producers of NBC's <i>Friends</i> deserve much credit. Since
it first aired, I have been a regular viewer and, like so many
of my peers, Thursday nights are often built around watching the
show with my own friends.
<p>
<i>Friends</i> is effectively scripted and produced.  The acting
is very good, the humor is both subtle and edgy, and they add
just the right measure of sappiness.  In short, it is very well
done, as evidenced by its number-one rating.
<p>
Another reason <i>Friends</i> is a hit is its relevance.  There
are tons of us whose lives, in so many ways, mirror those of the
characters.  We are young, single and dealing with life by facing
good days and bad, exceptional and mundane -- but all interwoven
with ribbons of humor, questions about our careers, and (of course)
romance. Sometimes we wish we could bottle these days and make
them last forever and sometimes we wish we had &quot;do-overs.&quot;
But whatever these days are like, many of us are fortunate enough
to walk through them with real-life friends, without whom life
would be much poorer.  This is the point on which <i>Friends</i>
is most compelling.  Its creators are to be commended on their
uncanny insight into our lives.
<p>
The one point at which the show diverges from reality is in its
portrayal of  moral dilemmas.  In episode after episode the producers
create life-like chances to demonstrate sexual propriety and nearly
every time, they fail.  The consistency with which they present
sexuality so tritely indicates one of two things:  they either
sell real-life people far too short, or they are working overtime
to thrust an &quot;it never costs anything and everything goes&quot;
view of sex upon us all.
<p>
This is not to say that sexual issues are not a significant part
of real life. But it is undeniable that  -- in the real world
-- sex for sport is not free, and most folks know it.  In the
deepest part of us, we know casual sex has an emotional and psychological
cost that is far greater than its momentary gratification.  Hence
the term we assign to the morning-after departure, &quot;the walk
of shame.&quot;
<p>
In the sobriety of the morning light, or when we're sitting on
our beds alone late at night, we are all too aware that there
is a hole in our hearts that sex alone can never fill. We also know 
that by acting as if sex can fill that void, we sure can enlarge the 
emptiness in our own life and in that of another.
<p>
As much as we may sometimes want it to be, we know sex is not
the way <i>Friends</i> portrays it.  We know a guy can't sleep
with a producer to get a part on a soap opera and then laugh it
off without losing his dignity and a whole lot more.  We know
a wife can't leave her husband for a lesbian lover and have the
&quot;wedding&quot; of the two women be warm and wonderful for
all concerned -- especially when their child will be raised by
her and her.  Good wit doesn't make everything okay, and one-liners
don't ameliorate the blisters random sex leaves on our hearts.
<p>
We know sex yields real freedom, safety, and lasting pleasure
only when it's enjoyed with the one friend to whom we have pledged
our life:  our husband or wife.  That friend doesn't have to go
home to shower before work, or wonder who might have shared the
same bed the week before.  That friend doesn't have to wonder
why her partner didn't call, or joke with the guys at the office
about not calling when he said he would.
<p>
So, despite the many ways the makers of <i>Friends</i> look at
our lives and seem to &quot;get it,&quot; when it comes to sex,
they obviously don't.

<p>
-- 2/6/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Larry H. Huff is the Director of State &amp; Local Affairs
for the Family Research Council, a non-profit educational organization
in Washington, D.C. that addresses public policy issues and cultural
concerns.</i>

<p>

<center>
<b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/perspective/">Other Perspectives</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/policypapers.html">Other Policy Papers</a>]
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/reproduce/reproduc.html">Reproducing This 
Article</a>]
</b>

<p>
<hr size = 3>
<p>

<a href="/townhall/FRC/images/navstrp2.map">
