<title>JANE AUSTEN COMES TO AMERICA</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>JANE AUSTEN COMES TO AMERICA</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Brent Vukmer</i></center>

<p>

I fall in that demographic group, &quot;Guys who prefer <I>Home
Improvement</I> to <I>Masterpiece Theater</I>,&quot; but I recently
went to see <I>Sense and Sensibility</I> anyway -- and liked it.
I'm not the only one.  Emma Thompson's film adaptation of Jane
Austen's book has grossed more than $21 million in its first few
weeks -- not bad for a limited-release, highbrow movie.
<p>
Hollywood is in a Jane Austen frenzy.  Starting last year with
<I>Clueless</i> (an updated <I>Emma</I>) and continuing in a big
way with <I>Sense and Sensibility</I>, this unassuming Dead White
Female has taken center stage in Hollywood.  <I>Persuasion</I>
is now on movie screens nationwide.  Another version of <I>Emma</I>
will appear in 1997.
<p>
Suddenly, Jane Austen is all over American pop culture. <I>People</I>
magazine included Jane Austen in their list of &quot;The 25 Most
Fascinating People in the World.&quot;  Press coverage in <I>Time</I>
magazine, <I>The Washington Post</I>, <I>The New York Times</I>, and 
other major media outlets has all been glowing.
<p>
What's going on?  How is it that Jane Austen, one of the most
tradition-minded women ever, shares press space with the cast
of <I>Friends?</I>
<p>
Pondering the question in the January 29th issue of <I>Newsweek</i>, 
Evan Thomas' article, &quot;Hooray for Hypocrisy&quot; concludes
that America misses having a society &quot;in which people ...
minded their manners.&quot;
<p>
Is that it?  Are we nostalgic for &quot;a more decorous and polite
age&quot;?  The 3.7 million households that tuned into A&amp;E's
six-hour version of <I>Pride and Prejudice</I> after the Super
Bowl <b>could</b> be explained away as a mutiny on the part of
Austen lovers and Miss Manners fans, recapturing the TV remote
after suffering through the pro football season.  Jane Austen
has always been popular with that segment of the population that
likes &quot;romance...cleverness...and some nice scenery.&quot;
<p>
But Thomas misses the point, I think.  Emma Thompson's <I>Sense
and Sensibility</I> <b>does</b> have romance, clever one-liners,
nice scenery, and exquisite manners, but Jane Austen has something 
important to offer besides her <I>Masterpiece Theater</I> qualities.
Colonel Brandon and Elinor are the heroes of <I>Sense and Sensibility</I>
because they are <b>good</b>:  kind, brave, strong, and trustworthy.
They keep their promises and steer by fixed moral principles,
not feelings.
<p>
That sounds more like it.  Americans are hungry for virtue.  In
a 1995 survey, the Family Research Council found that 66 percent
of Americans believe our society is &quot;on the wrong track.&quot;
Sixty-one percent of those surveyed attribute this to &quot;the
breakdown in the family and a decline in values.&quot;
<p>
Our nation's leaders seem to agree with most Americans.  Newt
Gingrich is talking about renewing America.  Not too long ago,
President Clinton admitted to Ben Wattenberg that, as Wattenberg's
recent book proclaims, <I>Values Matter Most</I>.
<p>
Former Secretary of Education Bill Bennett's various books about
old-fashioned values have been on national best-seller lists for
more than a year.   More than two million copies of <I>The Book
of Virtues</I> are in print, along with one million copies of
<I>The Children's Book of Virtues</I>, and 600,000 copies of
<I>The Moral Compass</I> in its first three months.
<p>
The bottom line?  It's not manners, but morality, that's in demand.
Parents are concerned more that their children might turn out
cruel than coarse.  This makes sense, because when two preteens
recently threw a grade-schooler to his death from an eighth-story
window because he would not steal for them, something more than
bad manners was at work.
<p>
Some modern experts on love, sex, and decision-making -- people
like former Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders -- assert that old-fashioned
morality is an out-of-date, ineffective prescription for society's
ills.  Out-of-date?  Even in Austen's tightly-edited version of
18th century life, single-mother households, premarital sex, and
illegitimacy were facts of life.
<p>
Is &quot;just say no,&quot; her prescription for the problems
of premarital sex, ineffective? William Bennett's wife Elayne,
a sort of 20th century &quot;daughter&quot; of Jane Austen, runs
a program called <I>Best Friends.</I>  It works with fifth- to
ninth-grade girls, promoting abstinence.  Out of the 400 D.C.
girls who have gone through the program so far, only one has become
pregnant.
<p>
Jane Austen was an entertainer, not a social scientist, but she
seems to have known something about home improvement that has
escaped Joycelyn Elders and other experts.  Maybe we <i>could</i> 
take a clue about love, sex, and the rest from her work.
<p>
Americans are flocking to Jane Austen movies because there aren't
many happy endings in our society.  For us, as Evan Thomas notes,
love, sex, money, and marriage aren't the ingredients for comedy.
&quot;Somehow,&quot; he says, &quot;letting it all hang out did
not bring freedom, just child-support payments, and the sexual
revolution bequeathed us AIDS and date rape.&quot;  Maybe the
experts should go to the movies.  Jane Austen's ideas make sense.
<p>
She knew that absolute truths make comedy possible.  The time-honored
traditions and codes that have always protected marriage and the
family provide a safe environment to pursue true love, to laugh
at life's follies, and to cry at weddings.  (Not that a die-hard
Tim Allen fan would ever go so far as to do <b>that</b>, of course.)

<p>
-- 2/8/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<I>Brent Vukmer is Correspondence Assistant at the Family Research
Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and advocacy organization.
He is currently working on a book about finding virtue on the
Internet.</I>

<p>

