<html>

<title>BOGUS ARMY STUDY CLAIMS WOMEN CAN BE AS TOUGH AS MEN</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>BOGUS ARMY STUDY CLAIMS<br>
WOMEN CAN BE AS TOUGH AS MEN</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Lieutenant Colonel Robert L. Maginnis (U.S.A., Ret.)</i></center>

<p>

Last spring, the Army Research Institute of Environmental Medicine
in Natick, Mass., selected 40 civilian women between the ages
of 18 and 32 from the Boston area to engage in physical training
for 24 weeks.[1] Funding for the study came from a $20 million
Defense Department women's health research project, pushed by
Rep. Patricia Schroeder (D-Co.).[2]
<p>
The study, which was released January 26, 1996, will certainly
be used by feminists to advocate removing more combat exemptions
for women.
<p>
For six months, these women trained five days per week and 90
minutes each day.   They lifted weights, hiked with backpacks
and ran twice a week.   The training was overseen by experts in
strength training and conditioning.
<p>
The $140,000 study found that after training, 78 percent of the
women could lift more than 100 pounds.[3] That qualifies them for
&quot;very heavy&quot; military occupational specialties which
are generally limited to men.  This finding would seem to cast
doubt on current female exemptions.
<p>
The volunteers increased their repetitive lifting ability,  improved
by one-third their time carrying a 75-pound backpack, increased
their aerobic ability by 14 percent and increased their hip and
thigh muscle strength and endurance dramatically.
<p>
Lori Gilstrap, a strength and conditioning coordinator with the
U.S. Olympic Committee,  said she wasn't surprised by the results.
She warned, however,  that women shouldn't be expected to match
men in strength because they have much lower levels of testosterone.[4]
<p>
Everett Harman, the Army scientist who headed the study, countered
that, &quot;You don't need testosterone to get strong.&quot; 
Consistent training and conditioning &quot;can be very effective
in improving the ability of women to perform physically demanding
military jobs.&quot;[5]
<p>
The study on its face is suspect, because it didn't include a
male control group which would have provided a comparison in change
in strength.  Had such a control group existed, it is likely that
the outcomes would have shown that a higher percentage of males
would have qualified for &quot;very heavy&quot; military specialties.
<p>
The study also failed to address the impracticality of  keeping
women at that high physical standard especially when they are
away from the &quot;artificial&quot; lab environment without barbells
and Olympic trainers.  Is it proposed that a cadre of special
staff be organized to sustain the level of strength and fitness
necessary for women to be effective in combat?
<p>
There are many reasons to exclude women from combat including
the fact that women typically lack the essential physical strength
and endurance for survival.  Numerous government studies have
advised against pushing women into physically demanding military
jobs.  A General Accounting Office report which was done in the
late 1970s found that &quot;a large number&quot; of women in the
military were assigned to specialties that were too physically
demanding.[6]
<p>
A 1982 Army study concluded that the Army's ground combat mission
would be hampered if women were continually assigned to tasks
they could not physically perform.   The study found that women
were only 58 to 78 percent as capable as men in five measures
of fitness.[7]
<p>
These studies are now being ignored.  Feminizing the Army is politically
correct.  During President Clinton's first three years the Army
has been radically changed to admit more women, even though there
is no compelling reason to do so other than to satisfy the demands
of political correctness.
<p>
Secretary of the Army Togo West cheers military feminization.
He has said, &quot;Readiness will improve [after lifting more
combat exemptions for women] because we will have a larger pool
of quality soldiers from which to draw to fill critical jobs.&quot;[8]
<p>
West's any-sex-fits-all view clashes with the advice of many experienced
leaders. As Desert Storm hero and commander General Norman Schwarzkopf
testified to Congress, &quot;Decisions on what roles women should
play in war must be based on military standards, not women's rights.&quot;[9]
Regardless of the logic expressed by senior military commanders,
feminists remain dead-set on putting more women into harm's way.
<p>
Sherri Boulay, one of the women in the new study, believes some
women can qualify for ground combat &quot;with special training
and skills.&quot;  Certainly a few can qualify, but the military
recruits by category, and women as a category lack the requisite
physical strength.  Why should the Army incur the burden of conducting
special training to qualify a small number of women when there
are fully qualified men already available?
<p>
Mixed-sex training was tried in the late 1970s and discontinued
because it hurt male performance.  Recently reintroduced mixed-sex
basic training has changed, however.   There is more emphasis
on technical than physical skills.  The physical requirements
have been relaxed.  Running is now done in lightweight shoes rather
than boots.  During the running of the mandatory obstacle course
recruits are allowed to go around the wall if they can't climb
it.  Overnight bivouacs may be canceled because of rain.  Marching
routes are changed to avoid tough hills.  Is the enemy listening?
<p>
Major General Gene Deegan, commander at the Parris Island Marine
Corps Recruit Depot, warned the 1992 Presidential Commission on
the Assignment of Women in the Armed Forces, &quot;If I were to
maintain the same intensity for [women in training as] the male
recruits, I would have a very difficult time recruiting any females,
and if my recruiting mission remained the same, I would fail in
my recruiting mission.&quot;[11] The question must be asked, &quot;Is
recruiting the mission or is fighting wars the mission?&quot;
<p>
Reducing the physical training demands for soldiers is ill-advised
even if it enhances cross-gender &quot;cohesion.&quot;  Cross-gender
cohesion is the goal of social experimentation.  It must not be
the goal of a lean, mean, fighting machine.  This ignores the
stark realities of the battlefield and the physical differences
between the genders.
<p>
The 1992 Presidential Commission ran a study to investigate whether
women could meet the same physical fitness standards as men. 
It found that only 3.4 percent of women achieved a score equal
to the male mean score on the Army's physical fitness test.[12]
<p>
Women experience more than twice the number of lower extremity
injuries and over four times the number of stress fractures, the
report said.[13]
<p>
Without special training, the commission found, nature gives women
only 50 to 60 percent of the upper torso muscular strength of
men.  They have 70 to 75 percent of the aerobic capacity of men.[14]
<p>
The United States Military Academy requires all cadets to complete
an indoor obstacle course test.   The test evaluates a cadet's
muscular strength/endurance, flexibility, agility, and coordination.
The average completion time for the 10 obstacles is 2:50 (min:sec)
for men and 4:05 (min:sec) for women.[15]
<p>
Even in the civilian world, rational minds recognize the fundamental
differences between the physical capacities of men and women.
Dr. Mary Lloyd Ireland, a Kentucky orthopedic surgeon, studied
why female basketball players suffer twice as many serious knee
injuries as males and six times more anterior cruciate ligament
tears.  She attributes the problem in part to the fact that women's
bodies are less-suited than men's to absorb the driving and pounding
of sports.[16]
<p>
Ann Loucks, an associate professor of physiology at Ohio University,
found that hard physical work coupled with a caloric deficit
may have long-term effects  -- damaging a woman's reproductive
ability and losing bone minerals, which could lead to osteoporosis.
Extended periods of hard labor and limited caloric intake are
common military conditions.[17]
<p>
Because of undeniable differences in speed, strength and endurance
between men and women, women will always be in greater danger
than men on the battlefield -- just as they are in some urban
&quot;combat zones.&quot;  In terms of modern-day combat, women
do not have &quot;an equal opportunity to survive.&quot;
<p>
Good physical condition is important for both sexes.  But the
most physically demanding assignments should go to men who are
genetically predisposed to handling the toughest tasks.  If special
training is offered, it should go to men to give them an edge
over our enemies.  Even the best and strongest females are unlikely
to match most male enemies.
<p>
America's military is on a slippery slope.   Feminists and their
supporters want to gender-neutralize the military by incrementally
ditching commonsense policies.  This latest study, which claims
that women can be trained to be like men, contributes to this
misguided ideology, weakens the force structure at its core, and
puts America's military personnel in peril.

<p>
-- 2/19/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Colonel Maginnis is the director of the Military Readiness
Project with the Family Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based
research and advocacy organization.</i>

<p><hr><p>

