<html>

<title>WHY MY SON SHOULDN'T FEEL LEFT OUT</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>WHY MY SON SHOULDN'T FEEL<br>
LEFT OUT ON &quot;TAKE OUR<br>
DAUGHTERS TO WORK DAY&quot;</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>William R. Mattox, Jr.</i></center>

<p>

In an ironic twist, the Ms. Foundation is being accused of gender
discrimination for excluding boys from their third annual &quot;Take
Our Daughters to Work Day.&quot;  In fact, a number of major companies
-- including Ford Motors, Polaroid, Colgate-Palmolive, and Apple
Computer -- are sufficiently concerned about appearances of sexism
that they are pointedly inviting both girls and boys to the workplace
for &quot;Take Our <I>Children</I> to Work Day.&quot;

<p>

While these companies' &quot;gender-inclusiveness&quot; and respect
for &quot;diversity&quot; is certainly commendable, I don't plan
to bring my 7-year-old son, David, with me to work on April 25.
Don't get me wrong.  I think boys have no less need than girls
to learn about the importance of work.  I'm just not convinced
that the most important work I do is done in the workplace.

<p>

That's why I devoted a day recently to staging my own little celebration.
I call it, &quot;Stay Home With Your Son Day.&quot;  And it was
quite a blast.

<p>

The day began with breakfast, followed by a trip outside to the
driveway, where I had David help me with some of the routine car
maintenance tasks (checking the oil, adding some radiator fluid,
cleaning the dashboard, etc.) that I used to help my father do.

<p>

After we finished, David and I ran some errands together.  We
stopped by the candy store to pick up some chocolates for me to
give to my wife when she and I celebrate our upcoming wedding
anniversary.  And we dropped by the post office to mail some letters
and survey the newest stamps -- just as I used to do with my grandfather,
who was an avid stamp collector.

<p>

In the afternoon, David and I enjoyed one of our all-time pastimes
-- playing wiffle ball in the front yard -- and then spent some
time before dinner working David's USA map puzzle and reviewing
some of his latest school work.

<p>

But the highlight of the day came at bedtime.  After I tucked
David in and shared in his nighttime prayers, I reviewed with
David some of the day's activities and told him something I learned
from my father (who, no doubt, learned it from his dad).  Here's
what I said:

<p>

&quot;David, there are lots of things I don't know and that I'll
never figure out.  But one thing I've learned is that some of
the most important work a man ever does is the work of being a
father. It involves things like teaching your children new skills,
showing them how a man should treat the woman he loves, building
family memories that will last long after you're dead and gone,
and telling your children about the never-ending love of the Father
above.  Now, David, this may not seem like a big deal.  But you
are growing up at a time when many men seem to think that all
of life's greatest joys are found in building and doing and working
away from home. They don't seem to understand how important the
job of a father is. They don't know how much joy marriage and
children can bring to life.  And the crazy thing is, David, a
growing number of women are acting like these men.  They seem
to think the best things in life are found in the workplace, too.&quot;

<p>

And then, after I kissed David goodnight and headed for the door,
I turned to him and said, &quot;Someday, son, you're going to
be a man.  And when you are, I hope that you will have a job that
you enjoy and that you do well.  And I hope you will marry a woman
just like your mother and have children just like ours.

<p>

&quot;When that day comes, David, I want you to remember the things
we've talked about today.  I want you to remember to honor and
cherish your wife.  And to make time with your children a top
priority.&quot;

<p>

-- 4/23/96

<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>William R. Mattox, Jr is vice president for policy at the Family
Research Council in Washington, D.C.</i>

