<html>

<title>GOVERNMENT SHOULD NOT PUSH ANTI-WOMAN MATERIAL</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>GOVERNMENT SHOULD NOT PUSH<br>
ANTI-WOMAN MATERIAL</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Lieutenant Colonel Robert L. Maginnis (U.S. Army, Retired)</i></center>

<p>

In a recent letter, a female U.S. Army officer based in Bosnia
told the Family Research Council that pornography &quot;degrades
the command atmosphere of respecting fellow soldiers and adds
to the possibility of misconduct....It is offensive to women serving
in the armed forces to be subjected to the rampant presence of
pornography.&quot;  The feelings expressed by this soldier are
shared by many others, and the end result is a decrease in morale,
unit integrity and overall readiness.

<p>

Some men want pornography to stimulate their sexual desires, but
this does not justify the government selling it to them at a discount
and tax-free.  That's why Rep. Roscoe Bartlett (R-M.D.) amended
the 1997 Defense Authorization Act to include language banning
future military sales of pornographic material.  This bill will
be debated in the House on May 15.

<p>

Government vending of pornography through the military exchange
system sends the message that profiting from material that demeans
women is okay.  This message is becoming increasingly unwelcome
to a growing cohort of female soldiers.  In fact, common sense
and science tell us that readily available pornographic material
encourages, rather than discourages, episodes like Tailhook, the
rape in Okinawa, and a sailor groping a female airline passenger.

<p>

It also hurts retention.  The Pentagon makes a big deal of family
issues because half of all military members are married.  For
many military spouses, who often are limited to shopping at government
exchanges, the sale of pornography is not only offensive, but
pornography consumption can be a contributing factor to the breakdown
of a marriage.  You can bet this impacts their husbands' retention
and, in effect, ratchets down military readiness yet another notch.

<p>

An Air Force wife complained that at her local exchange &quot;pornography
is viewed and then carelessly discarded on lower shelves, on top
of children's comic books, and I've seen one on an ice cream machine
at our base convenience store that children frequent after school.&quot;

<p>

The target of the bill is pornography, not romance novels or classic
art.  Pornography is Greek for &quot;depictions of the activities
of whores.&quot;  It is, by definition, sexually explicit and
intended primarily for the purpose of sexual arousal.  The Uniform
Code of Military Justice labels many of the activities described
and shown in this material as criminal if done by a servicemember.

<p>

There is a growing body of science which points to a direct association
between the consumption of pornography and sexual misconduct.
This should be a red flag for the military, which is experiencing
increased levels of sexual misbehavior.

<p>

The 1986 Attorney General's Commission on Pornography cites studies
which show that over half of rapists say they were &quot;incited
to commit an offense&quot; by pornography and that 42 percent
of child molesters &quot;implicated pornography&quot; in their
crimes.

<p>

A book by Don Gibbons, <I>Society, Crime, and Criminal Behavior</I>,
a copy of which is in the Pentagon library, cites a national study
that found that readership of sexually explicit magazines like
<I>Hustler</I> and <I>Playboy</I> (both of which are sold in military
stores) were highly correlated with rape rates.

<p>

Dr. Victor Cline, a clinical psychologist at the University of
Utah, chronicled the stages of addiction to pornography based
on his work with over 200 sex offenders.  He found that pornography
is a powerful stimulant that requires ever more explicit images
in order to reach the previous level of sexual arousal.  At some
point the addict may act out sexual fantasies inspired by the
material.

<p>

Pornographic material may also be a form of sexual harassment.
Sociologist Diana Russell states in her paper &quot;Pornography,
A Feminist Perspective&quot; that &quot;pornography is vicious,
anti-woman propaganda.  It tells lies about us.  It degrades women.
Pornography is not made to educate but to sell and, for the most
part, what sells it is a bunch of lies about sex and women.&quot;

<p>

Why does the Pentagon refuse to dump this material?  The contention
is that &quot;any attempt to prohibit the sale of magazines currently
available through the exchange services would raise serious constitutional
and administrative problems.&quot;  But the issue is not really
about constitutional rights, it is a matter of money.  Selling
smut in government stores is a big business decision.

<p>

The Pentagon sells 12.6 million copies of 219 different pornographic
magazines every year.  Its earnings are $4.3 million.  Customers
pay less than the market price and pay no tax.

<p>

Pornography is also the third highest profit industry in organized
crime -- after narcotics and gambling.  The FBI estimates the
pornography industry to be an $8-10 billion-a-year enterprise.

<p>

This is not a freedom of speech issue, because no one is advocating
denying soldiers the opportunity to buy legal pornography off
base and keep it in their barracks.

<p>

The Pentagon should not have constitutional concerns but moral
ones. Few federal judges would force the military to sell pornography,
those who would ought to become candidates for impeachment.

<p>

The constitutional obligation in this area belongs to Congress.
That obligation is to protect the military's combat fitness.
Under Article 1, Section 8, the Congress is duty bound to set
the rules and regulations for the military.  If Congress declares
that selling pornography is bad for readiness, then it has both
the right and obligation to rid exchange shelves of the smut.
The Supreme Court generally gives Congress special deference
in matters affecting the military.

<p>

Unfortunately, some base commanders, wishing to remove this material
from exchanges, have been told &quot;no&quot; by bureaucrats.
The threat of lawsuits has intimidated them.  There are some
exceptions, however.

<p>

The captain of the carrier <I>America</I> received a complaint
about a magazine sold in his ship's store.  The April 1984 issue
of <I>Hustler</I> magazine included graphic pictures of a woman
engaged in a sex act with a crucifix.  The ship's supply officer
was ordered to deep-six the magazine, and the order went unchallenged.

<p>

Marine commanders at Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, ignored bureaucrats
when it came to a local purveyor of pornography.  Eugene's Arcade
was placed &quot;off limits&quot; to military personnel.  When
the shop owner filed a suit alleging violation of his rights of
free speech, federal judge W. Earl Britt dismissed it, concluding,
&quot;A military commander has an overriding duty to safeguard
the morals, welfare and discipline of his men.&quot;

<p>

President Clinton has unilateral authority to remove pornographic
material from military stores.  His executive order could prohibit
such sales all over the world, but there is no evidence the White
House is about to sign such an order.

<p>

That leaves the Congress with the responsibility to pass the Military
Honor and Decency Act.  It is the right thing to do.  It will
enhance readiness and reduce the cancer-like spread of pornography
that contributes to sexual misconduct.

<p>
-- 5/10/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Robert Maginnis is a retired Army lieutenant colonel and the
director for the Military Readiness Project with the Family Research
Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and educational organization.</i>

<p>

