<html>

<title>THE LEAST OF THESE</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>THE LEAST OF THESE</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Jennifer E. Marshall and Deanna Carlson</i></center>

<p>

Does increased social spending equate with better childhoods?
For lack of a better answer, both Republicans and Democrats have
been inclined to say &quot;yes.&quot;  Spending by the federal
government on social programs for children and families has increased
dramatically since 1960, far exceeding the rate of inflation.
Yet, almost all indicators suggest that more children today are
living just this side of despair than was true three decades ago.

<p>

Social spending advocates made their mistake in expecting government
to substitute for mothers and fathers.  Noted child psychologist
Urie Bronfenbrenner has written that what children need more than
government programs is the &quot;irrational emotional attachment&quot;
of parents who love them fiercely.  Even Bill Clinton stated in
his acceptance speech at the 1992 Democratic National Convention
that &quot;governments do not raise children -- parents do.&quot;

<p>

It's time to take the rhetoric seriously and to acknowledge that
government can't buy love for children any more than money can
buy happiness for adults.  What children really need is a mom
and a dad.

<p>

<center><h3><i>Parents, Not Programs</i></h3></center>

<p>

Rather than winking at government's creeping encroachment on families,
Congress should move quickly to pass pending parental rights legislation
(S. 984; H.R. 1946).  The legislation would neither create new
rights for parents nor repeal child abuse laws that protect children
when families break down.  The new law would simply protect parents'
rights to decide what is best for their children without excessive
interference from Washington.

<p>

Having affirmed the central importance of parents, government
does sometimes have a role to play in helping parents care for
the young ones in their charge.  One good example is &quot;Megan's
Law,&quot; which Congress has just passed and the President signed.
The new law requires states to notify local law officials when
convicted sex offenders are released from prison and requires
local police to notify the public when a sex offender who is deemed
dangerous moves into the local neighborhood.

<p>

<center><h3><i>Yes to Adoption</i></h3></center>

<p>

The community, of course, must step in to provide for children
who have no parents to call their own.  But the importance of
parents remains the same  -- and probably greater -- for children
who are alone.  The best government can do is to speed a child
on his way into a loving home where adoptive parents are prepared
to love him fiercely and forever.

<p>

&quot;The Adoption Promotion and Stability Act of 1996&quot;
(H.R. 3286), passed by the House but not yet the Senate, could
open windows of hope for vulnerable children currently free to
be adopted.  In the United States alone, there are more than 50,000
foster children hoping to be adopted.  More than 20,000 children
have been waiting for a family for a matter of years.  The new
legislation includes a $5,000 non-refundable tax credit for qualified
adoption expenses (for both domestic and international adoptions).
In order to eliminate unnecessary waiting periods for minority
children in foster care, the legislation also prohibits the use
of racial considerations if they cause a delay or denial of an
adoption placement.

<p>

<center><h3><i>No to Foster Care</i></h3></center>

<p>

New adoption incentives will help some children, but Conna Craig,
President of the Institute for Children, argues that nothing less
than an overhaul of the foster care system will save children
like John.  A skinny kid who loves baseball, John has been waiting
for a home for nearly all of his 10 years.  Legally free to be
adopted since he was 3 years old, John is a prisoner of the system
whose childhood is fast slipping away.  He needs policymakers
to understand that standing for children means giving every child
a chance to have a mom and a dad.

<p>

<center><h3><i>It Takes a &quot;Village&quot;</i></h3></center>

<p>

Even strong two-parent families require strong communities to
help pattern for children right habits of the heart.  When so
many children are languishing without families of their own, community
becomes all the more important.

<p>

&quot;The American Community Renewal Act of 1996,&quot; spearheaded
by Congressmen James Talent (R-Mo.) and J.C. Watts (R-Okla.),
will strengthen communities more than any government handout could
by offering tax incentives for charitable giving, public housing
reform, and an end to government regulations that stifle economic
development in depressed neighborhoods.  By rebuilding communities,
we stand to strengthen the hands of parents -- and to restore
some of childhood's lost innocence.

<p>

It's right and fair to admit that it takes a village, as long
as we really mean a local &quot;village&quot; that preserves parent
autonomy, instead of a federal plantation that chains both children
and families to an all-powerful state.

<p>

<i><b>To contact Conna Craig at the Institute for Children, please
call (617) 491-4691.</b></i>

<p>
-- 5/23/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Jennifer E. Marshall is a policy analyst at the Family Research
Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and educational organization.
Deanna Carlson is FRC's community outreach coordinator.</i>

<p>

