<html>

<title>WHY SO MANY AMERICANS OPPOSE THE CAREERS BILL</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">

<p>

<h2>WHY SO MANY AMERICANS OPPOSE<br>
THE CAREERS BILL</h2></center>

<hr size = 3 width = 50%>

<p>

Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) recently circulated a &quot;Dear Colleague&quot;
letter expressing his concerns about the education agenda embodied
in Goals 2000, School-to-Work, and most recently, CAREERS.  In
defense of their CAREERS legislation, Rep. Bill Goodling (R-Pa.)
and Rep. Buck McKeon (R-Calif.) sent a &quot;Dear Colleague&quot;
letter which attempted to address Mr. Hyde's concerns.

<p>

Regrettably, neither the Goodling/McKeon responses nor the changes
made to the CAREERS bill since its introduction have resolved
the central issues that trouble Mr. Hyde, pro-family groups, conservative
economic groups, and thousands of families across the country.
The following central provisions are unacceptable:

<p>

<b>The creation of a workforce development infrastructure.</b>
The CAREERS bill requires the creation of state and local workforce
development boards that will oversee all aspects of the &quot;seamless
system&quot; of workforce development.  These boards will be appointed,
not elected.  The system has more resemblance to centrally planned
industrial policy than to the American free market tradition.
The jurisdiction of the workforce development boards will include
programs for in-school youth, thereby infringing on the authority
of locally elected school boards.

<p>

<b>The Labor Market Information System (LMIS).</b> This system
would include &quot;<B>comprehensive</B> information on the socioeconomic
characteristics, and current employment status of the population,
including self-employed, part-time, and seasonal workers&quot;
(Title II, Sec. 21-22).  The Senate bill even requires the collection
of social security numbers so that wage data may be maintained
on individuals.  Furthermore, this national LMIS would be controlled
at the federal level by the U.S. Secretary of Labor.  LMIS thus
poses an ominous threat to personal privacy and should be rejected
on that basis.  But even if LMIS did not invade personal privacy,
it would still be an underfunded mandate to states and an inefficient
mechanism for helping people get jobs.  Why should the government
duplicate the labor market trend speculation already provided
by numerous employment agencies, trade organizations and business
journals?

<p>

<b>The inclusion of youth in a seamless system of workforce development.</b>
The needs of youth are much different from those of an unemployed
adult.  Vocational education should be a matter left to the local
control of elected school boards, not merged into a complex new
workforce development infrastructure.

<p>

We would welcome true block grant reform that would give states
authority to run job training according to their needs.  CAREERS,
however, <B>creates</B> a new system and more red tape by establishing
the workforce development infrastructure and expanding the Labor
Market Information System.

<p>

Following are some reactions to the responses made by Mr. Goodling
and Mr. McKeon to Mr. Hyde's letter.  The statements in italics
are taken directly from the Goodling-McKeon letter, including
their paraphrases of Mr. Hyde's concerns.

<p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Is the CAREERS bill &quot;designed to advance
the School-to-Work phase of Goals 2000?&quot;  Are the roots of
this legislation tied to the work of the Clinton Administration?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: No.  CAREERS is the product of Republican
efforts going back to the Reagan and Bush Administrations.  It
incorporates suggestions by a bipartisan coalition of reform-minded
colleagues, including many leading Republican Governors.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>I.</b> Don't forget the liberal ideas embodied in CAREERS.
Soon after Mr. Goodling introduced his National Workforce Preparation
and Development Reform Act (H.R. 2943), predecessor to CAREERS
in the 103d Congress, Sen. Ted Kennedy introduced a similar measure
in the Senate, the Job Training Consolidation and Reform Act (S. 2516).

<p>

According to <I>Congressional Quarterly</I> &quot;key components
of H.R. 2943 [Mr. Goodling's bill] were similar to language in
H.R. 2884 (<B>School-To-Work Opportunities Act</B> of 1993),&quot;
which the House passed on Nov. 15, 1993.  School-to-Work was President
Bill Clinton's second major education initiative.  Goals 2000
was the first.  CAREERS carries on the national system of workforce
development in School-to-Work and Title V of Goals 2000 (the National
Skill Standards Act of 1994).

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Does CAREERS reference Goals 2000?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: No.  Nothing in this bill requires any State
to participate in Goals 2000, or to adopt education standards
or related education programs.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>II.</b> CAREERS would require a state to participate in a
program much like that of Title V of Goals 2000 (the National
Skill Standards Act of 1994).  Under this title, the National
Skill Standards Board is charged with developing a national system
of skill standards, skill certificates and skill assessments.

<p>

These elements are undeniably present in the CAREERS bill.  CAREERS
cites the National Skill Standards Board [Sec. 108(c)(3)], supports
government involvement with industry-approved standards [Sec.
110(f)(1)(D)] and supports the creation of skill certificates
[Sec 5(41)].

<p>

Of course there is no overt reference to Goals 2000, but the philosophy
of Goals 2000 is present in CAREERS:  &quot;experts&quot; and
government join together to recognize national standards which
are to be emulated by state and local participants as they fulfill
the requirements of the act.

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Does CAREERS require funds be used to implement
tech-prep, career counseling, or other career-related programs
at the earliest possible age?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: No. Prior to House floor consideration,
all references to elementary education and to serving youth &quot;at
the earliest age possible&quot; were deleted from the bill.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>III.</b> Actually, Mr. Hyde's letter expressed this
concern about the <I><B>Senate bill</B></I> (S. 143), where career
guidance and counseling at the earliest possible age are still
<I><B>mandated</B></I> [Sec. 106(b)(3)].

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Does CAREERS require youth to pass &quot;performance
outcome assessments determined by the National Skill Standards
Board,&quot; that would replace high school diplomas?  Or require
that students at age 16 (10th grade) be placed in either vocational
training classes or apprenticeships?  Does CAREERS require that
students who are not prepared to enter vocational classes by age
16, be &quot;placed in youth centers&quot;?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>:  Absolutely not. Neither the House CAREERS
Act, nor the Senate workforce legislation contain any such requirements.
Neither bill mentions &quot;10th grade assessments,&quot; &quot;certificates
of initial mastery,&quot; or &quot;outcome-based education.&quot;
There is no requirement that students be tracked in vocational
or apprenticeship programs, or placed in &quot;youth centers.&quot;</i>

<p><ul>

<b>IV.</b> While CAREERS does not itself include these elements,
how does it guard against them?  This bill <B>will</B> advance
the work of the National Skill Standards Board, promote skill
certificates and certificates of initial mastery and shift American
public education toward a new model -- the <B>German</B> model,
as cited by staff last year.  Proponents of CAREERS have forgotten
that the bill is not entering a void and that implications beyond
its exact language must be considered.

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Why are industry-recognized skill standards
referenced in the bill?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: Because the youth title of CAREERS is not
broad education reform -- but is the consolidation and reform
of vocational education and job training programs for drop-outs
and disadvantaged youth -- we found it appropriate to ask that
these programs reflect the skill needs of local employers, so
that such education and training is relevant.  These are young
people who decide they want to get a good job at the end of their
school years (that may very well include postsecondary education
and training)....</i>

<p><ul>

<b>V.(a)</b> To the contrary, it has not been made clear that
the CAREERS bill will not bring broad change to education as a
whole because the term &quot;in-school youth&quot; is not defined
in the bill.  Also, a &quot;comprehensive system of workforce
development and literacy&quot; [Sec. 101, purpose] implies that
it could involve everyone -- in school and out.  State plans must
tell how the academic and occupational skills of youth will be
developed [Sec. 221(1)].  No qualification is made to the term
&quot;youth&quot; in this context, so whether its authors intended
it or not, it is likely that regulation could require the inclusion
of <I><B>all</B></I> youth.

<p>

FRC and other groups have expressed concerns that students not
be steered into vocational fields.  <B>If the rationale for including
youth in this seamless system is to ensure that in-school &quot;programs
reflect the skill needs of local employers,&quot; how will the
steering of students according to employers' needs be avoided?</B>

</ul><p>

<i><b>RESPONSE (cont.):</b> Nothing however, requires States
or localities to use &quot;national&quot; skill standards, established
by the National Skill Standards Board.  There are two references
in the bill to skill standards adopted by the National Skill Standards
Board, and both are <b>voluntary</b>.  Such standards <b>may</b>
be used by States, in determining the performance of adult training
providers.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>V.(b)</b> The point is that CAREERS endorses the federally
funded work of the National Skill Standards Board (that is, creating
a national skill standard system) instead of repealing it.

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Will CAREERS require the award of skill certificates?
Can skill certificates be used to replace high school diplomas?
What are skill certificates -- are they same as certificates
of initial mastery?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: Certificates of initial mastery are <b>not</b>
referenced in CAREERS.  Skill certificates are <b>not</b> certificates
of initial mastery.  They do <b>not</b> take the place of a high
school diploma.  Skill certificates are <b>not</b> mandatory in
CAREERS.  Skill certificates are a portable credential that <b>may</b>
be awarded to individuals once they have attained occupational
skills at levels that industry has recognized as necessary to
do a specific job/occupation.  As previously cited, there is language
in the bill that specifically says that nothing in the Act can
be used to require any individual to acquire a skill certificate
or to meet industry-recognized skill standards.  Further, language
was added to the bill clarifying that skill certificates may only
be awarded to youth, <b>in addition to or in combination with
a high school diploma</b> or a G.E.D.  Further, skill certificates
are not imposed upon employers.  In other words, an employers'
use or recognition of skill certificates for purposes of hiring,
is <b>totally voluntary.</b></i>

<p><ul>

<b>VI.</b> In School-to-Work jargon, &quot;certificate of initial
mastery&quot; and &quot;skill certificate&quot; <I><B>are</B></I>
used interchangeably.  State applications for federal School-to-Work
grants alternate between the two terms.

<p>

When government gets involved in the creation of skill standards
and certificates to be considered in hiring, government has the
potential to become gatekeeper to the workforce.  Also, consider
the logic of the national skill standards system, written in law
(Title V of Goals 2000).  Skill certificates are useful only if
they give preference to the people who have them.  There is little
use in having a skill certificate system if it is not universal,
so it is highly unlikely that the system will stay voluntary for
long.  That is why many Americans were looking to this Congress
to <B>uproot</B> the national skill standards system begun under
Goals 2000 and the School-to-Work Opportunities Act of 1994 and
are highly disappointed to see the same elements retrenching in
the form of CAREERS.

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Does CAREERS move us toward &quot;dumbing-down&quot;
education in the U.S.?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: No.  One of the few requirements under the
youth component of CAREERS is for the integration of academic,
vocational, and work-based learning.  This is to ensure that vocational
education and training for disadvantaged youth is not &quot;dumbed-down&quot;
-- to ensure that these programs stress academics as well as occupational
learning.  CAREERS also requires that secondary and postsecondary
institutions develop articulation agreements, so that students
in vocational education have access and are encouraged to go on
to postsecondary education.  Nothing in CAREERS discourages independent
achievement.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>VII.</b> Proponents of CAREERS have forgotten that the bill
is not entering a void, but an educational atmosphere of dumbed-down
academics and controversial values.  Mr. Hyde is right to communicate
the concerns of many parents that CAREERS could contribute to
such problems because the school-to-work agenda already in place
has detracted from the academic purpose of schooling.  Again,
it has not been sufficiently proven that CAREERS will be any different,
because its reach into education remains unclear and potentially
extensive.

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Does the CAREERS bill result in a &quot;managed
economy&quot; where federal, state, and local workforce boards
will control all job programs through one-stop or integrated career
centers?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: No.  The whole point of the CAREERS bill is
to empower individuals (through vouchers and a competitive system)
to make their own informed career choices, and to assist States
and local communities in making reforms in job training and vocational
education programs to meet individual needs.</i>

<p>

<i>In exchange for billions of dollars in federal funding for
job training and employment assistance, CAREERS does ask States
and localities to establish integrated career center systems --
easily accessible, single points of entry into local employment
and training  programs -- for adults in need of employment assistance
or job training, and for employers who are in need of workers.
The actual design for such systems is left entirely to the
State and local community.  co-located Career centers (some call
them one-stops) are encouraged, not required.  And they are locally-designed,
appointed, and managed -- <b>not federally-run or controlled</b>.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>VIII.</b> The state and local workforce development boards
mentioned in the concern above will not be elected and will therefore
not have to answer to voters.  The boards are charged with developing
a comprehensive education and workforce development system for
their communities.  Since it has not yet been clarified that CAREERS
will not affect all in-school youth, it may be assumed that these
boards will have significant authority over not only labor and
economic issues in their regions, but also over education.  Like
Goals 2000's establishment of appointed school improvement councils
at the state and local levels, such <B>workforce development boards
will take authority away from locally elected bodies such as city
councils and school boards.</B>

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Does CAREERS establish &quot;a computer-based
system that will track teachers' training and performance, school
performance, and ...students from pre-kindergarten through technical
training and into the workforce&quot;? Will CAREERS require that
&quot;all information will be made available to interested government
officials and prospective employers&quot;?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: No. The CAREERS bill does <b>not</b> allow
for the collection of private information on any individual --
especially youth.  Protections are included in the bill to address
this concern as follows...

<p><ul>

<li>Specific language restating Title 13 of the Census Act relating
to confidentiality of information was added to the bill prior
to its floor consideration.

<p>

<li>Specific language that states:  &quot;Nothing in this Act
shall violate the Family Education Rights and Privacy Act under
section 249 of the General Education Provisions Act and the privacy
and confidentiality provisions under section 22(b) of Title II
of the Wagner Peyser Act as amended by this Act,&quot; was also
added.

<p>

<li>Language was added requiring that all data collected as part
of the labor market information system be aggregate data from
the census and other public sources -- not personal information.

</ul><p>

<b>Adult Training Performance-based Program Information.</b>
There is language in the bill requiring States to collect performance
data on adult job training providers that want to participate
in the voucher program.  Such performance-based information is
necessary to allow individuals to make their own, informed career
choices.  Submission of such information is voluntary however,
required only if training providers want to receive federally-funded
training vouchers.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>IX.</b> The Labor Market Information System (LMIS)
database of workforce information is to be &quot;<B>comprehensive</B>,&quot;
supplying information on &quot;the socioeconomic characteristics,
and current employment status of the population, including self-employed,
part-time, and seasonal workers, and individuals with severe disabilities&quot;
and &quot;job vacancies&quot; and so on [Title II, Sec. 21-22].

<p>

Combine such an idea with the Smart Cards Gov. Miller boasts of
in Nevada and the Worklink electronic resume in other states --
both of which gather data on school children -- and Americans
are right to be alarmed about the potential for invasion of their
privacy and that of their children.

<p>

Though CAREERS' version of LMIS may not include data that invade
personal privacy, setting up this vast new database system to
be uniform throughout the nation is worrisome.  At any time in
the future, if government should decide to require <b>additional</b>
data on individuals, the LMIS will be at their fingertips.

<p>

LMIS is really a Catch-22.  On the one hand, to provide unique,
powerful data, LMIS would have to threaten personal privacy. 
On the other hand, if it is sufficiently watered down to protect
individuals, LMIS will largely duplicate the type of data already
provided by a number of trade and business sources in the private
sector.  Either way, LMIS should not be a government endeavor.
It's a waste of money.

</ul><p>

<i><b>CONCERN</b>: Will CAREERS require individuals to receive
a government chosen job, or require individuals to receive a government
card in order to obtain and to hold a job?  Would the bill require
employers to list jobs with the labor market information system,
or require employers to hire individuals who have received skill
certificates as a result of job training programs?</i>

<p>

<i><b>RESPONSE</b>: No. The CAREERS bill does not tell individuals
what jobs or careers they must hold.  The bill has no references
to government cards or requirements for employment.  Individuals
have the freedom to select any job or career they want.  In fact,
CAREERS increases this liberty, empowering individuals through
the use of vouchers, to obtain the job training of their choice.
Further, the CAREERS bill does not place any requirements on
employers, for purposes of job listings, or hiring practices.</i>

<p><ul>

<b>X.</b> It bears repeating:  the Labor Market Information
System (LMIS) database of workforce information is to be &quot;comprehensive,&quot;
supplying information on &quot;the socioeconomic characteristics,
and current employment status of the population, including self-employed,
part-time, and seasonal workers, and individuals with severe disabilities&quot;
and &quot;job vacancies&quot; and so on [Title II, Sec. 21-22].
If those aren't requirements of employers, what is?

<p>

If it truly will be voluntary for employers to submit data to
LMIS, why should the government be doing this when the private
sector already provides sufficient labor market information supplied
on a voluntary basis by employers?

</ul><p>

<center>
<b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/infocus/">Other In Focus</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/policypapers.html">Other Policy Papers</a>]
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/reproduce/reproduc.html">Reproducing This 
Article</a>]
</b>

