<title>HOSPITAL VISITATION: A NON-ISSUE</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">

<p>

<h2>HOSPITAL VISITATION:<br>
A NON-ISSUE</h2></center>

<hr size = 3 width = 50%>

<p>

Homosexual activists often say that a key reason they need same-sex
&quot;marriage&quot; is because they are denied hospital visitation
rights to see their lovers.[1]

<p>

Yet an informal survey of hospitals in the Washington, D.C. area[2]
and elsewhere reveals that no institution bars any visitor that
the patient cares to see.  When asked if a patient had been denied
the right to a visit by a homosexual lover, hospital administrators
responded with incredulity that it was even considered an issue.
None recalled anyone being barred from seeing a patient because
of the visitor's homosexuality.

<p>

Homosexual activists cite a single case in which a lesbian lover
was barred from seeing a disabled patient at a mental hospital
and then at home with the patient's parents because of the wishes
of the patient's family.[3] A Nexis search on July 1, 1996 revealed
no other cases in which a homosexual was barred from visitation
by a family.  Yet homosexual activists give the impression that
the problem is widespread and that the only way to overcome this
barrier is to allow homosexuals to &quot;marry,&quot; thus elevating
them to &quot;family status.&quot;

<p>

The activists also often claim that the patient's family has final
authority in all instances of hospital visitation.  But final
authority most often is the patient, who is permitted to define
the &quot;intimate circle&quot; of visitors.  In fact, patients
routinely see anyone they want.

<p>

Typically, the choice falls to the family only when the patient
is unable to make the decision.  Families rightfully have this
authority, since ties of blood, adoption and genuine marriage
outweigh other types of relationships.  This would apply in cases
where the patient is sedated or unconscious and has not made previous
arrangements (such as a &quot;living will&quot;).  The homosexual
&quot;hospital visitation myth&quot; is derived from such a scenario.

<p>

According to hospital administrators, an unmarried couple, heterosexual
or homosexual, can define their &quot;intimate circle&quot; in
writing in what is called a &quot;proxy.&quot;  That request will
be honored regardless of whether the patient's family agrees.
Patients can also grant power of attorney to homosexual lovers,
giving them legal authority and access equal to that of family.
As far as HIV-infected patients are concerned, courts routinely
have confirmed the visitation rights of  children to see an HIV-infected
parent (in or out of the hospital).[4]

<p>

The only person with higher authority than the patient is the
doctor.  If the doctor believes the presence of a certain person
will adversely affect the patient, then the doctor has the authority
to revoke that person's visitation rights, even if that person
is a family member.

<p>

These policies are not newly instituted concepts but have been
in existence for years.  In rare cases where patients feel they
have been inconvenienced by current policy,  redress is available
through appeal to hospital authorities, local law or through professional
medical associations.

<p>

<center><h3>CONCLUSION</h3></center>

<p>

The homosexual movement's &quot;hospital visitation hardship&quot;
is an emotional smokescreen without foundation that is being used
to distract from the more serious implications of radically redefining
marriage.

<p>

-- 7/2/96

<p><hr><p>

<h3><center>ENDNOTES</center></h3>

<ol><font size=-1>

<p>

<li>This point frequently is made in radio and television
debates.   For example, on the June 3, 1996 edition of <I>The
Diane Rehm Show</I>, a program syndicated on National Public Radio,
the point was made during a debate in which homosexual activist
Elizabeth Birch and homosexual Congressman Barney Frank (D-MA)
argued for homosexual &quot;marriage&quot; and against the proposed
federal Defense of Marriage Act.

<p>

<li>Telephone survey by Family Research Council Cultural
Studies Research Assistant Kenneth Ervin II in June and on July
1, 1996 of George Washington University Hospital, District of
Columbia General Hospital, Alexandria Hospital, Arlington Hospital,
Lake Charles Memorial Hospital and St. Patrick's Hospital in Lake
Charles, Louisiana, Beth Israel Hospital in Boston, Massachussetts,
Buffalo General Hospital in Buffalo, New York and Lincoln Memorial
Hospital in New York City.  The response was uniform.

<p>

<li>Joyce Murdoch, &quot;Fighting for Control of a Loved
One; Guardianship Dispute Pits Disabled Woman's Partner, Family,&quot;
<I>The Washington Post,</I> August 5, 1988, p. A-1.

<p>

<li>Nan D. Hunter, Sherryl E. Michaelson, Thomas B.
Stoddard, <I>The Rights of Lesbians and Gay Men</I>, (Carbondale
and Edwardville:  Southern Illinois Press, 1992), p. 145.

</ol></font><p>

